cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.SY, cs.DS 

Reasoning: 
- cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is the most likely category as the paper proposes a scheduling protocol for MIMO ad-hoc networks with contention-based medium access. 
- cs.IT (Information Theory) is also likely as the paper discusses the tradeoff between feedback requirements and system throughput. 
- cs.MM (Multimedia) is relevant as the paper exploits spatial multiplexing and diversity to improve system throughput. 
- cs.SY (Systems and Control) is relevant as the paper proposes a threshold policy derived from optimal stopping theory. 
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is less likely but still possible as the paper proposes a new scheduling protocol that takes into account physical channel conditions.
